TY  - JOUR
AB  - I. Exaggeration of economic importance of reparation payments. 1. Political influences. 2. Emphasis on transfer problem. II. Summary of reparation payments. 1. Estimates of transfers up to 1924. 2. Dawes Plan payments according to source, currency used for transfers and means of transfer. 3. New Plan payments according to source and means of transfer. III. Economic background of reparation payments by Germany. 1. Internal factors. a. Relation to budget, especially debt and defense items. b. Connection with foreign loans. 2. External factors. a. Fallacy of pairing-off international payments. b. Volume of international transactions. IV. Power of forces creating equilibrium in international settlements.
